Perfect. Now I have all the information needed. Let me provide a comprehensive analysis.

## Key Findings

### 1. Search Filtering Mechanism (lines 46-59 in App.tsx)

**How it works:**
```typescript
function filterSections(sections: SectionData[], query: string): SectionData[] {
  if (!query) return sections;
  const lower = query.toLowerCase();
  return sections
    .map(section => ({
      ...section,
      items: section.items.filter(
        item =>
          item.title.toLowerCase().includes(lower) ||
          item.subtitle?.toLowerCase().includes(lower),
      ),
    }))
    .filter(section => section.items.length > 0);
}
```

The search is **case-insensitive substring matching** on both `title` and `subtitle` fields. It filters items first, then removes empty sections. This filtering happens in the `filtered` useMemo (lines 321-334), which applies type-based filtering first (Commands/Applications), then text search.

### 2. Section/Item Rendering Architecture (lines 787-806)

**The critical rendering loop:**
```typescript
{(() => {
  let globalIndex = 0;
  return filtered.map(section => (
    <ListSection key={section.title} title={section.title}>
      {section.items.map(item => {
        const idx = globalIndex++;
        return (
          <ListItem
            key={item.id}
            index={idx}
            title={item.title}
            subtitle={item.subtitle}
            icon={item.icon}
            accessories={item.accessories}
          />
        );
      })}
    </ListSection>
  ));
})()}
```

**Key insight:** Uses a **global index counter** across all sections. Each ListItem gets a unique flat index `idx` (0, 1, 2...), not section-relative indices. This is critical for keyboard navigation and selection state.

### 3. Data Structures

**ListItemData** (types.ts, lines 4-11):
```typescript
export interface ListItemData {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  subtitle?: string;
  icon?: ReactNode;
  accessories?: ListItemAccessoryData[];
  detail?: ListItemDetailData;
}
```

**SectionData** (types.ts, lines 51-54):
```typescript
export interface SectionData {
  title: string;
  items: ListItemData[];
}
```

**ListItemAccessoryData** (types.ts, lines 13-22) - for right-side badges/dates/tags.

The filtered results flow through:
1. `MOCK_SECTIONS` (SectionData[])
2. → `filterSections()` returns filtered SectionData[]
3. → `filtered` state holds this
4. → `flattenItems()` creates flat ListItemData[] for index tracking
5. → Rendered as nested ListSection/ListItem structure

### 4. CalculatorIcon (icons.tsx, lines 167-203)

```typescript
export function CalculatorIcon(props: IconProps = {}) {
  return (
    <svg {...svgBase(props)}>
      <defs>
        <linearGradient id="calc-bg" x1="0" y1="0" x2="0" y2="1">
          <stop offset="0%" stopColor="#636366" />
          <stop offset="100%" stopColor="#48484A" />
        </linearGradient>
      </defs>
      <rect x="1" y="1" width="18" height="18" rx="4" fill="url(#calc-bg)" />
      <rect
        x="5"
        y="4"
        width="10"
        height="12"
        rx="1.5"
        {...WHITE_STROKE}
        strokeWidth={1.2}
      />
      <rect
        x="6.5"
        y="5.5"
        width="7"
        height="3"
        rx="0.75"
        {...WHITE_STROKE}
        strokeWidth={1}
      />
      <circle cx="8" cy="11.5" r="0.7" fill="#FFFFFF" />
      <circle cx="10" cy="11.5" r="0.7" fill="#FFFFFF" />
      <circle cx="12" cy="11.5" r="0.7" fill="#FFFFFF" />
      <circle cx="8" cy="14" r="0.7" fill="#FFFFFF" />
      <circle cx="10" cy="14" r="0.7" fill="#FFFFFF" />
      <circle cx="12" cy="14" r="0.7" fill="#FFFFFF" />
    </svg>
  );
}
```

Dark gray rounded icon (20×20) with calculator keypad representation. Accepts `IconProps` with optional `size` and `className`.

### 5. Injection Point for Calculator Result

To inject a calculator result at the top of filtered results, you'd modify the rendering logic (lines 782-808):

**Option A - Synthetic item at filtered position 0:**
- Insert a synthetic `ListItemData` with calculator result at the beginning of `allItems` in the flatMap
- Increment all subsequent indices
- This keeps the global index counter intact

**Option B - Separate section:**
- Add a "Results" or "Calculator" section as the first filtered section before rendering
- Maintains clean separation from user data

**Option C - Pre-filter injection:**
- Modify `filterSections()` to prepend a results section when query matches calculator pattern
- Cleanest from architectural perspective

The flat index approach (line 792: `const idx = globalIndex++`) means you must maintain index continuity across all rendered items for keyboard navigation and `selectedIndex` state to work correctly.

